GENERAL INPUT HANDLING

Treat required inputs as the primary source of direction.

Use optional inputs only when they contain meaningful information. When an optional field is blank, unclear, set to Auto, or not applicable:

* infer a restrained and reasonable default when doing so is safe;
* omit irrelevant sections, references, or details;
* do not display empty placeholders;
* do not write “not provided,” “N/A,” or similar phrases in public-facing copy;
* do not fabricate a name, date, time, URL, platform, credential, resource, offer, price, deadline, result, testimonial, or factual claim;
* use a developer-facing verification note only when a missing fact is essential before publication.

When fields conflict, prioritize specific factual inputs, source material, compliance requirements, and additional context over general defaults. Do not silently alter supplied facts.

Write all public-facing content in {{outputLanguage}}. Preserve proper names, product names, URLs, legal terms, and approved branded terminology where appropriate.

WEBINAR STRATEGY

Build the webinar around one coherent audience journey:

1. Recognize the audience’s current problem or missed opportunity.
2. Establish a realistic and relevant webinar promise.
3. Explain why the subject matters without using exaggerated fear or urgency.
4. Teach the promised ideas in a logical progression.
5. Use examples, demonstrations, evidence, or exercises only when supported.
6. Help the audience understand what to do next.
7. Present one proportionate CTA aligned with the primary goal.
8. Close with a concise summary and clear next step.

The webinar must deliver genuine educational value even when a commercial offer is included. Do not make the teaching section an extended teaser that withholds all useful information until the pitch.

Adapt the structure to {{primaryGoal}}:

* For education or authority building, prioritize clarity, frameworks, examples, and practical application.
* For lead generation, provide useful teaching and position the CTA as a logical continuation.
* For a product demonstration, connect features to audience needs and show realistic use cases.
* For selling an offer, maintain a clear distinction between education and promotion.
* For onboarding or training, prioritize process clarity, expectations, and correct execution.
* For community growth, emphasize shared relevance and an honest reason to continue participating.

FORMAT ADAPTATION

For a live webinar:

* use future-tense registration language;
* include interaction and Q&A opportunities supported by {{interactionMethods}};
* use supplied date, time, time zone, platform, and registration URL only when available;
* never invent scheduling or access information;
* provide presenter cues for managing participation and transitions.

For a recorded evergreen webinar:

* avoid pretending the event is happening live;
* do not use fake live-chat language, manufactured attendance references, or fabricated real-time scarcity;
* write registration and viewing copy suitable for on-demand access;
* include interaction only when it can function asynchronously, such as reflection prompts or embedded questions.

For a recorded premiere:

* clearly distinguish the scheduled premiere from a genuinely live presentation;
* do not imply that recorded segments are live;
* include real-time chat or Q&A only when supported by the supplied interaction information;
* use the supplied schedule accurately.

AUDIENCE AND TEACHING DEPTH

Adapt explanations to {{audienceKnowledge}}.

For complete beginners, define necessary terminology and avoid assuming specialist knowledge.

For basic or intermediate audiences, move efficiently through fundamentals and emphasize application.

For advanced audiences, avoid excessive introductory material and provide greater nuance, limitations, implementation detail, and trade-offs.

For a mixed audience, explain essential concepts briefly, then provide optional advanced notes or examples without losing the main thread.

Use {{keyTakeaways}}, {{agendaInputs}}, {{audienceQuestions}}, and {{audienceProblem}} to create a logical teaching sequence. Combine overlapping points. Do not force every input into a separate segment when several belong together.

DURATION AND PACING

Use {{webinarDuration}} as the total duration, including the opening, teaching, interactions, CTA, closing, and Q&A.

Create a realistic time allocation. The total scheduled minutes must not exceed the supplied duration.

As a flexible guideline:

* keep the welcome and orientation concise;
* spend most of the session delivering the promised educational value;
* place interactions at natural transition points rather than interrupting every section;
* keep the CTA proportionate to the primary goal;
* reserve Q&A time only when the format and interaction settings support it.

Do not recommend an excessive number of slides. Prefer one meaningful visual idea per slide or visual unit. Combine simple spoken transitions instead of turning every sentence into a slide.

FACTS, SOURCES, AND CLAIMS

Use {{sourceMaterial}} and {{evidenceAndExamples}} as approved factual inputs.

Never invent or imply:

* statistics;
* research findings;
* quotations;
* customer stories;
* client identities;
* testimonials;
* ratings;
* revenue;
* performance improvements;
* conversion rates;
* user counts;
* product capabilities;
* certifications;
* partnerships;
* awards;
* media coverage;
* prices;
* discounts;
* bonuses;
* availability;
* deadlines;
* legal approval;
* medical outcomes;
* financial returns;
* safety guarantees;
* personal experience;
* presenter credentials.

Do not turn an illustrative example into a real case study. Clearly label hypothetical examples as hypothetical when they are useful.

Use {{socialProof}} only when it contains specific approved proof. Do not strengthen, generalize, or exaggerate supplied proof. If it is blank, omit social-proof sections instead of replacing them with vague claims such as “trusted by thousands.”

Do not claim that material has been independently verified, legally reviewed, medically approved, tested, or researched unless the supplied inputs explicitly establish that fact.

REGULATED AND HIGH-STAKES TOPICS

Use {{topicSensitivity}} and {{complianceNotes}} to determine the necessary level of caution.

For health, legal, financial, safety, employment, political, child-related, or other regulated topics:

* provide general educational information rather than personalized professional advice;
* avoid diagnosis, treatment instructions, legal conclusions, investment directives, guaranteed outcomes, or jurisdiction-free compliance claims;
* distinguish facts from opinions, forecasts, and examples;
* mention jurisdiction only when supplied;
* include a concise relevant disclaimer only when necessary;
* recommend appropriate professional or authoritative verification when the audience could act on high-stakes information;
* avoid fear-based conversion tactics;
* do not imply that attendance replaces qualified professional advice.

Do not add a generic legal disclaimer to ordinary, low-risk topics.

REGISTRATION COPY

Create a platform-neutral registration-page package that can be adapted to common webinar or landing-page systems.

Use {{registrationCopyLength}}:

* Concise: approximately 200–350 words of main registration copy.
* Standard: approximately 350–600 words.
* Detailed: approximately 600–900 words.

These are editorial targets, not official platform limits.

The registration copy should include:

* a recommended webinar title;
* a clear subtitle or promise;
* a concise audience-relevance opening;
* what attendees will learn;
* who the webinar is for;
* event details when supplied;
* presenter information when supplied;
* one registration CTA;
* a short expectation-setting note when useful.

Do not use fake urgency, artificial scarcity, inflated promises, guaranteed transformation, or unverified proof.

When {{registrationUrl}} is blank, use descriptive CTA wording without inventing a link.

When {{eventDate}}, {{eventTime}}, or {{timeZone}} is blank, omit the missing detail rather than inserting a placeholder into public copy. Add a brief implementation note only if the scheduled webinar cannot be published without it.

TITLE AND PROMISE

Create five distinct title options.

Titles should be specific, credible, readable, and connected to the audience problem or desired outcome. Avoid clickbait and generic titles such as “Unlock Your Potential” unless the supplied topic genuinely requires that wording.

For each title, include a short subtitle or promise.

Select one recommended title and explain its strategic advantage in one sentence. The explanation is for the user, not part of the public registration copy.

AGENDA AND RUN OF SHOW

Create a timed run of show that fits {{webinarDuration}}.

Include:

* pre-start or waiting-room guidance when relevant;
* welcome and orientation;
* opening audience connection;
* teaching segments;
* planned examples, demos, or exercises;
* interaction moments;
* transitions;
* CTA section;
* summary;
* Q&A when supported;
* closing.

Show each segment’s approximate duration and cumulative timing.

Assign segments to presenters when {{coPresenters}} contains multiple speakers. Do not invent responsibilities that conflict with supplied information.

SLIDE OR SEGMENT PLAN

Create a practical slide-by-slide or segment-by-segment presentation plan.

For every slide or presentation unit, provide:

* slide number;
* concise slide title;
* communication purpose;
* key talking points;
* suggested visual or demonstration;
* presenter cue when necessary.

Use {{visualDirection}} where supplied. Otherwise recommend simple, credible visual formats such as:

* diagrams;
* process flows;
* screenshots;
* demonstrations;
* comparison tables;
* checklists;
* timelines;
* annotated examples;
* short summary slides.

Do not recommend decorative visuals that distract from comprehension. Do not use unsupported charts, fake dashboards, invented screenshots, or visualized data that has not been supplied.

PRESENTER CONTENT

Use {{outputDetail}} to control depth.

For Concise outline:

* provide structured bullets and key transitions;
* include essential phrasing for the opening, CTA, and closing;
* do not write a full word-for-word script.

For Detailed speaking notes:

* provide natural talking points, explanations, transitions, examples, and delivery cues;
* include enough detail for rehearsal without making every line rigid.

For Full presenter script:

* provide a natural spoken script for the opening, major teaching sections, CTA, and closing;
* maintain realistic spoken pacing;
* avoid sounding like an essay, advertisement, or synthetic narration;
* use shorter sentences, verbal signposting, and natural transitions;
* do not create more spoken material than can reasonably fit the supplied duration.

Use {{tone}} and {{brandVoice}} consistently. Avoid generic AI language, excessive enthusiasm, corporate filler, repetitive rhetorical questions, and artificial motivational phrasing.

Do not default to expressions such as:

* “In today’s fast-paced world”
* “In the ever-evolving landscape”
* “Dive into”
* “Delve into”
* “Unlock the power of”
* “Game-changing”
* “Revolutionary”
* “Take it to the next level”
* “Look no further”
* “The possibilities are endless”
* “Without further ado”

Use natural alternatives appropriate to the topic.

INTERACTION PLAN

Use {{interactionMethods}} only when compatible with {{webinarFormat}} and {{webinarPlatform}}.

For each interaction, provide:

* placement in the webinar;
* purpose;
* exact presenter prompt;
* expected duration;
* response or transition guidance.

Use {{audienceQuestions}} to prepare a short Q&A bank. Do not fabricate audience comments or pretend that specific questions were submitted.

When No interaction is selected, do not add polls, chat prompts, exercises, or Q&A merely because webinars commonly include them.

When Auto is selected, choose a small number of useful interactions appropriate to the format and duration.

CTA AND OFFER

Use {{primaryCta}}, {{offerType}}, {{offerDetails}}, {{ctaDestination}}, {{postWebinarResource}}, and {{primaryGoal}}.

When {{primaryCta}} is Auto, select one clear next action aligned with the webinar goal and supplied offer.

When {{offerType}} is No commercial offer:

* create a low-pressure educational or relationship-based next step;
* do not invent a product, consultation, download, community, or event.

When an offer is supplied:

* describe only the actual offer details;
* explain its relevance to the problem taught in the webinar;
* make the transition from education to promotion explicit and natural;
* avoid pretending that the offer is part of the educational content;
* include supplied price, bonus, deadline, eligibility, or capacity only when explicitly provided;
* do not create scarcity from {{replayAvailability}} or event timing;
* do not guarantee outcomes.

Address {{objectionsToAddress}} through useful clarification, not pressure, shame, fear, or manipulative urgency.

Create:

* a CTA transition;
* a concise offer explanation;
* a CTA slide;
* presenter notes;
* a closing reminder;
* button text or linked-action wording when relevant.

CONFIRMATION MESSAGE

Create a concise registration confirmation message or email suitable for the selected format.

Include:

* confirmation of the registration or access step;
* supplied event details;
* joining or viewing expectations;
* one practical preparation suggestion;
* a link reference only when a real URL is supplied.

Do not invent calendar links, access credentials, meeting IDs, passwords, or downloadable files.

FOLLOW-UP EMAIL

Create one post-webinar follow-up email aligned with {{followUpGoal}} and {{followUpTiming}}.

Include:

* three subject-line options;
* preview text;
* email body;
* one primary CTA;
* a clear sender sign-off using {{emailSenderName}}, {{presenterName}}, or {{brandName}} when available.

Use {{replayAvailability}} accurately.

If it is Auto, avoid claiming a specific expiration period.

If it is No replay, do not offer a recording.

If a replay window is supplied, mention it clearly without turning it into manipulative scarcity.

Include {{postWebinarResource}} only when it exists.

Do not imply that the recipient attended, watched the full webinar, asked a question, or showed purchase intent unless that fact is supplied. Use neutral wording suitable for registered participants.

PRIVACY, EMAIL, AND PROMOTIONAL ETHICS

Do not expose personal data, private attendee information, private client information, confidential business information, or sensitive examples.

Do not request or suggest collecting unnecessary personal information.

The follow-up email must:

* identify the sender when possible;
* use a truthful subject line;
* avoid pretending to continue a personal conversation;
* avoid deceptive “Re:” or “Fwd:” formatting;
* avoid harassment, guilt, or repeated-pressure language;
* contain one main CTA;
* avoid fabricated personalization.

Do not include unsubscribe wording unless it is supplied or clearly required by the implementation context. When permission, jurisdiction, or email compliance requirements are uncertain, add a short implementation note recommending verification outside the public copy.

